<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="578" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1190,1541]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1226,1252]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1887" box="[328,473,1227,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Metopininae">Metopininae</taxonomicName>
. Body matte brown. Frontal macrosetae golden brown instead of black. Lacking dense black setulae on scutum; instead scutum with scattered golden-brown setae. Hind tibia without setal palisades or rows of setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1190,1541]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">
This genus is differentiated from most other metopinines by the lack of dense setulae on the scutellum (as discussed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, B. V." box="[263,406,1371,1397]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref5700" refString="Brown, B. V. (2007) A further new genus of primitive phorid fly (Diptera: Phoridae) from Baltic amber and its phylogenetic implications. Contributions in Science, 513, 1 - 14. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / p. 241295" type="journal article" year="2007">Brown 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, B. V. &amp; Amorim, D. S. &amp; Kung, G. A." box="[419,628,1370,1397]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578" pagination="424 - 485" refId="ref5884" refString="Brown, B. V., Amorim, D. S. &amp; Kung, G. A. (2015) New morphological characters for classifying Phoridae (Diptera) from the structure of the thorax. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 173, 424 - 485. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zoj. 12208" type="journal article" year="2015">
Brown 
<emphasis box="[503,560,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). An exception that also lacks dense dorsal scutal setae is 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Platydipteron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">Platydipteron balli</emphasis>
Brown
</taxonomicName>
; however, that species has a shiny black body and is strongly limuloid in body structure.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="578" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1190,1541]" box="[199,1351,1443,1469]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1443,1469]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">Etymology.</emphasis>
From Latin for “gold-bristled phorid”, referring to the color of the main setae on the body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1190,1541]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,1478,1505]" pageId="7" pageNumber="578">Natural history.</emphasis>
Unfortunately, we know nothing about these flies, other than their propensity to fly into Malaise traps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
